And honestly, that's all I really know about Ireland. Not much else was said or told to us. Just the potato stuff. And that Bono is from there.

Goodnight.

It's part 2!

I remember being fascinated and horrified when one boy from our year claimed that, on holiday in Dublin, he was served spaghetti bolognese with potatoes instead of pasta.

There were also rumors of chilli served with potatoes. But that actually sounds good.

Happy St Patrick's Day to all who celebrate. 

Growing up in Scotland I'd hear lots of wild stories about our cousins from the emerald isle. Foremost: That they love and crave potatoes so much, that they include them in all forms of cuisine. 

Part 2 to follow! 🇮🇪

I say all this to say: Let's go back to the days when all you needed to qualify was a receipt from CVS and valid ID.

Remiss of me not to say that I came to this country with many advantages and privileges. I have good credit and steady income. And it's still really hard to get a mortgage. I imagine other folks face many more obstacles.

It would appear I underestimated just how difficult it is to get a mortgage in America. 

I've always been hesitant when it comes to opening up credit cards, or store cards, and accumulating massive amounts of debt and bills.

But turns out ... that stuff is desirable. Mental eh?

All of these people make the show. Together. With the host.

So, to conclude this thought, I'd love to see people credit more than just the host when they write about shows.

Narrative, documentary-style podcasts are incredibly collaborative. Producers are 🔑.  Like I said, oftentimes they are directing the movie that plays in your head while you listen.
Engineers elevate stories and bring new dimensions.
Editors don't just polish turds, they make

They may well pitch the story, set the structure, do a bunch of reporting, write it, work on sound design and give the piece a sonic identity. They may even spend a lot of time with the host producing their narration so it sounds right 👌

And yet, they are rarely named.

Late night 🌙 pod thought: As the industry grows and evolves, I'd love to see the way talent is credited in reviews/write-ups change. In most cases you'll get the host's name and that's it. 
Folks in the industry know that often producers are the equivalent of movie directors

Your brain, just like your body, can get a bit beat up. And, like your body, it needs time to recover. 

I say all this to say, more power to Naomi Osaka. Incredibly brave of her to prioritize her mental health. 

And imagine she told the press she pulled her hamstring ...

There's a worrying amount of distrust when anyone discloses that they are not doing well. 
"How can that be true? You're so good at tennis!" 
I think the truth is that many of us will experience a whole range of states of mental health. From tip top, to utter shite. And that's OK

A lot of the dialogue surrounding Naomi Osaka confirms how regressive, and frankly ignorant, so many are when it comes to mental health. 
This shit, like physical health, is a spectrum. It's not binary: Healthy or unhealthy. Sometimes you might be well, other times not so well.

to the message at the center of it: You are resilient. Your body is resilient. So's yer brain. You can weather this storm.

You can not find this man on ZocDoc, but in these trying times just buy a big ol' ham and recite these words over and over.

Turns out, he was right. I did start to feel better. And the sadness and hopelessness thawed. 

I often think about this man, this ham with a beard, and I wonder if he gave me good or terrible advice that day?

It's probably bad advice, isn't it? But I guess I always come back

And he said to me: "Well you could do therapy. Or talk to someone. There's medication. Or, you could do nothing."

NOTHING?🤔

"Yes. Nothing. Your body can only feel this bad for so long. It's not possible to sustain this. You'll be okay in a few months."

It's impressive and powerful. And I've thought about it a lot since I watched it. But it didn't move me and excite me the same way that other films have this year. Possibly because, even if I'd never seen Citizen Kane, I already knew the story.

At the end of the movie I found it hard to quantify how much I enjoyed it. It's widely regarded as the greatest film of all time. Like Star Wars, elements of it transcend and are ubiquitous in pop culture. Which makes it sort of impossible to judge in a vacuum. 

But: 8/10.

Some elements of the film are as dated as you'd expect from something that is 80 years old. The comic scenes seem to rely solely upon people tripping over things, or mishearing things. Yet, some of it feels entirely contemporary. And Welles still burns through the screen.

I guess I thought Kane would be worse. When I think of ruthless tycoons, my mind goes to men like Trump and to Murdoch. Kane's arrogant and self-serving. He treats people poorly. But he's not vile and irredeemable in the same way as men like Trump. Which, I guess, is good.

Is struck me that I had never seen Citizen Kane in its entirety. I'd seen pieces of it, fragments and jigsaw pieces like the memories collected in the plot, and I knew to look out for the sled. But I'd never seen it all. Until last night. It surprised me in a lot of ways.

Hears a thing and understands what's wrong with it. That's hard!
They then concisely explain what the problem is. That's hard too!

It's really, really, really hard. A proper intellectual high-wire act.

And Mr. [REDACTED] looks me in the eye and says: "It says more about you than it does about me, Matthew."
And I remember looking back at him and thinking, No it doesn't sir cos I don't like chickens the way that you like chickens. 

Probably got grounded for a month for that.

then there's this. 
😱
Mr. [REDACTED] produces my old jotter. Flips it open to a page featuring some sort sordid scenario involving him and a chicken and pushes it across the table to my mother. 
Wow. 
My mother is stunned into silence.

As per usual, my poor mother was in for a long night. I wasn't well behaved, nor did I get good grades. So, we get to the appointment with Mr. [REDACTED] and he gives me a surprisingly good report. There's potential there, I just lack focus. 
yeah
Lack concentration
yeah
And ...

The next day, nothing happens. No detention, no expulsion, no appointment with a psychiatrist. Nothing. NOTHING!
The days and weeks drift by. I forget about the chicken sketches and move on with my life.
Until Parent Teacher Meeting 1998. 
Next slide please ...

him leafing through the pages. Closer and closer to the chicken sketches until 
finally
he arrives at destination chicken fucker. He pauses. And looks up at me. Our eyes meet 👀 He knows and I know that he knows. Calmly, Mr. [REDACTED] stands up, picks up my book, and walks away.

One day Mr. [REDACTED] spots my friends and I hunched over my jotter, giggling. I quickly flip the pages to a recent exercise and play it off like I'd just told a joke. But the teacher could smell a rat/dead chicken and swiped my jotter. The color drained from my face as I saw ..

I started sketching Mr. [REDACTED] in compromising situations with his dead chickens. Or, to use modern parlance, entangled with these chickens. My jotter had pages of these sketches. They weren't hugely graphic, more surreal and comic. Disco dancing w/ chickens. Fine dining etc.

So I posit my theory to my friends. There's something going on with Mr. [REDACTED] and those chickens, I say. 
He's absolutely shagging those chickens, they say. 
Now, around this time I liked to sketch. And you can probably tell where this is going, can't you?
NEXT SLIDE PLZ.

We gathered outside the Barclays. Chanting and waving our signs while above our heads the huge digital advertising board beamed GEICO commercials. 
At around 7:30PM a protester turned to a nearby police officer: What happens at 8, you just start arresting us?

Protested tonight. I'm a worst-case-scenario kind of thinker. Was afraid that I'd get arrested. That my green card would be revoked. That I wouldn't be allowed to live in the US.
Then I remembered why I was protesting: So black men like George Floyd are allowed to live, period.
And I say this as someone who is struggling to check items off of that harder-to-do list. And as someone who is, right now, doing the easy thing and talking on social media.

I guess one thing I've been thinking about is how change is hard. Change is challenge. Posting on social media is literally the easiest thing you can do. How many of us use IG daily? It's not an imposition to post. 
Donating, voting, protesting, self-educating. All harder to do. https://t.co/CHU02GTqvF

Posting and sharing information is excellent. And I think we should all continue to do that. But it's maybe more meaningful to engage with this subject more deeply than throwing a tile up. And also just donating to bail funds + many orgs doing great work right now.

Look, it's been incredibly inspiring to see friends from back home posting black tiles and being galvanized to speak out. That's beautiful. But I'm old enough to remember Kony and other viral campaigns that didn't result in any meaningful change.

Like a lot of folks, I'm trying to be very thoughtful and deliberate about everything I say and do in this moment. Incredibly important to do your research and figure out if your actions are contributing to the cause, or accidentally undermining it.

Got through after 30 mins. During the hold music I tried ramming the bike about 50 more times. And somehow got the pedal lodged under the kickstand. 
Things were not going well.

Spent the next 10 minutes ramming the bike at the dock and hoping everything would magically slot into place. Must've looked absolutely mental. This bald man, thrashing a bike and swearing.
No bike docking miracle was delivered, so I had to admit defeat and call Citi Bike.

How on earth did this metal docking device end up flipped up like that? I have no idea. Best guess is that I, um, was a little heavy-handed in my first attempt to dock the bike. Got the angle wrong. And fucked up the bike. Maybe. 
Whatever happened, the bike could not dock.

In the pic above you'll notice a big metal triangle. Here it's pointing towards the sky and the heavens above. It's not meant to be, though. It's meant to assume a far less ecstatic posture. It's meant to point forward cos that's how it slots into the dock.

@BNEShrimper Yeah, I feel similarly. It's a shame, because it could have been something much more meaningful.
But ... It's still glorious in its own empty sort of way.

You have to wonder what might have happened if Jordan's life and legacy received the same treatment as a series like OJ Simpson Made in America, or any of the Asik Kapadia films. It might be uglier, but surely it would stick with you in a way that something this glossy never can.

The fact that many of us have gleefully mainlined two hours of this series every Sunday night speaks to its magnetism and power. And just the sheer adrenaline rush that comes with seeing all the old Jordan magic tricks set to a superb soundtrack. It's been such a joy, hasn't it?

Guess tonight's the last Last Dance, eh? 
It's an imperfect documentary series and, as others have written, comes dangerously close to becoming branded content and reveals v little about who Jordan really is.
But it's still been a phenomenal spectacle. And a much-needed time hop.
